es and mass imprisonment, but we also witness family members finding strength as they come together to demand justice for their loved ones. And while her own challenges as a young mother reveal the vast inequities of our healthcare system, Benjamin also describes how the support of doulas and midwives can keep Black mothers and babies alive and well.Born of a stubborn hopefulness, Viral Justice offers a passionate, inspiring, and practical vision of how small changes can add up to large ones, transforming our relationships and communities and helping us build a more just and joyful world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aActivismxSocial aspects. 0aEquality. 0aJustice. 0aRacial justicezUnited States. 0aSocial changezUnited States. 0aSocial justicezUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aAbleism.  aAffordable housing.  aAngus Deaton.  aBasic skills.  aBlack people.  aCT scan.  aCase study.  aChild care.  aChildbirth.  aCitizenship.  aClassroom.  aClinical trial.  aCommunity land trust.  aCounterintelligence.  aCovid-19.  aEmotional Intelligence.  aEmployment.  aEric Garcetti.  aEugenics.  aFemininity.  aGeographer.  aGleaners.  aGrandparent.  aGroup call.  aHate crime.  aHealth care.  aHousehold.  aHypocrisy.  aInnate intelligence.  aInstitution.  aJohnnetta B. Cole.  aLand mine.  aMedical history.  aMidwife.  aMs. (magazine).  aOpposition to immigration.  aOrganization.  aOrganizational culture.  aOwnership.  aPaternalism.  aPerson of color.  aPersonality.  aPlough.  aPolice officer.  aPolice.  aPoverty.  aProvision (accounting).  aPublic health.  aRacism.  aRedistribution of income and wealth.  aRidicule.  aSalary.  aShock and awe.  aSlavery.  aSocial order.  aSociology